## 4. Data Simulation

### WebSocket Server

Build a simple Node.js WebSocket server that pushes telemetry at exactly 10 Hz (every 100ms):

```typescript
// ws-simulator.ts
import { WebSocketServer } from 'ws';

const wss = new WebSocketServer({ port: 8080 });
const TICK_INTERVAL = 100; // 10 Hz
let sensorCount = 500; // configurable via query param

wss.on('connection', (ws, req) => {
  const count = parseInt(new URL(req.url!, 'http://localhost').searchParams.get('sensors') || '500');
  sensorCount = count;

  const interval = setInterval(() => {
    const readings: Record<string, { value: number; timestamp: number }> = {};

    for (let i = 0; i < sensorCount; i++) {
      readings[`sensor-${i}`] = {
        value: 20 + Math.random() * 80,  // 20-100 range
        timestamp: Date.now()
      };
    }

    ws.send(JSON.stringify(readings));
  }, TICK_INTERVAL);

  ws.on('close', () => clearInterval(interval));
});
```

### Threshold Rules for Alarm Testing

For every sensor:

- Yellow warning: value > 70
- Red alarm: value > 90
- Normal: value ≤ 70

With values randomised between 20-100, roughly 30% will be in warning and 10% in alarm on any given tick. This exercises the color-change code path continuously.

### Partial Update Variant (S5)

For scenario S5, only include 10% of sensors in each WebSocket message (randomly selected). This tests whether the renderer is smart enough to skip unchanged elements.

