## 10. Expected Outcomes & Decision Matrix

### If SVG-B handles S3 (500 components) at ≥30 FPS with ≤50ms alarm latency:

→ **Use SVG.** The developer experience advantages (DOM inspectability, CSS styling, native browser events, text crispness at zoom, existing Vue tooling) outweigh Canvas benefits. The monitoring pillar can use direct DOM updates bypassing Vue for the hot path.

### If SVG fails at S3 but Canvas-B handles it:

→ **Use Konva for the canvas area.** The layered architecture with direct Konva updates for monitoring provides the safety margin needed. Evaluate whether Configuration pillar authoring should also use Konva (consistency) or SVG (better authoring DX) — the hybrid approach.

### If both fail at S3:

→ Re-evaluate component count assumptions with the control engineer. 500 components with all sensors updating simultaneously at 10 Hz may not reflect reality. Run S5 (partial update) to test the realistic scenario.

### If both pass even at S4 (1000 components):

→ **Use SVG.** Performance is not a differentiator; choose the simpler technology.

---

## 11. What This Benchmark Does NOT Test

These items matter but are separate concerns:

- **Zoom/pan performance** — different test, add later if needed
- **Authoring interactions** (drag, drop, connect) — not a throughput problem
- **Electron IPC overhead** — this benchmark uses WebSocket directly; IPC adds a thin layer but is not the bottleneck
- **Memory over long duration** — run a separate 30-minute soak test for leak detection
- **Touch/mobile performance** — desktop application, not relevant

